snippet: The ruling came after the fourth inquest into the death of a 9-week-old girl. At one point, the girl’s mother had been convicted, though the verdict was later overturned.
abstract: Coroner in the inquest into the death of 9-week-old Azaria Chamberlain, 32 years after her death, rules that she died as a result of being taken by a dingo, a wild dog; ruling ends her family's long struggle to get an official ruling on the cause of death.

byline.contributor: Christine Kenneally contributed reporting from Melbourne, Australia.

lead_paragraph: The ruling came after the fourth inquest into the death of a 9-week-old girl. At one point, the girl’s mother had been convicted, though the verdict was later overturned.

headline.seo: After 32 Years, Coroner Confirms Dingo Killed Australian Baby
headline.main: After 32 Years, Coroner Confirms Dingo Killed Australian Baby
